column9: This is a stretch as Calassomys is a new genus based on a new animal that was caught. Calomys sorellus was picked only from a phylogenetic tree showing it as the most ancestral Calomys species and therefore closest to Calassomys
Or H. chacarius; H. lagigliai is based off of an old specimen collected far from other known Holochilus species and with mixed similarities/differences to closest geographic/morphometric species
O. oniscus realted to O. seuanezi, those related to O. capito, and those related to O. yunganus
New species in new area with no phylogenetics conducted. Any neusticomys would likely be just as good, but O. oyapocki and O. peruviensis appear to be geographically closest
No clear similarities, though these species have a similar geographic range and O. stramineus has the closest karyotype to O. rupestris

P. xanthopygus/darwini is a close second based on incorrect identification of at least 2 specimens. However, P. alisosiensis closely resembles anitae, and anitae/osilae are the only Phyllotis species to inhabitat the same habitat. Additionally, alisosiensis and anitae are sister taxa most closely related to osilae, giving an additional level of comparability
It most closely resembles R. microdon, but range limitations differ drastically. Instead, R. musseri was originally thought to be a juvenile R. rodriguezi

Distinct newly found species, separated geographically from both other Scapteromys species and looks significantly different, though morphologically and geographically closer to S. tumidus than S. aquaticus
